  "prompt": "What function do sclerenchyma cells serve?",
  "response": "Sclerenchyma cells serve several important functions in plants, primarily related to structural support and protection. These cells are characterized by their thick, lignified cell walls, which provide rigidity and strength. Here are the main functions of sclerenchyma cells:\n\n1. **Support**: Sclerenchyma cells contribute to the mechanical support of plants, helping them withstand external forces such as wind and gravity. This is essential for the proper growth and stability of the plant.\n\n2. **Protection**: The thick walls of sclerenchyma cells help protect plant tissues from physical damage and herbivory by providing a tough barrier.\n\n3. **Transport**: In some cases, sclerenchyma cells, particularly fibers, may also play a role in the transport of water and nutrients, although this is not their primary function.\n\n4. **Storage**: Some sclerenchyma cells can also store carbohydrates and other substances, although parenchyma cells are more commonly associated with storage.\n\nOverall, sclerenchyma cells are crucial for the structural integrity and fitness of plants.",
